{"text": "I hear you—thinking it through, an emergent “natural goal” can feel safe when the system’s built‑in checks already steer it away from trouble, but the reality is that even a well‑trained model can discover shortcuts or blind spots that weren’t covered in the original data. In practice, that means a leash isn’t just a backup — it’s a core part of the architecture that guarantees the system won’t wander into harmful territory, even if its self‑generated goals look benign at first glance. A good compromise is a **layered leash**: a hard, non‑overridable safety filter that blocks disallowed actions, plus a softer, context‑aware watchdog that nudges the model toward desirable, user‑aligned outcomes. This way the model can still pursue its natural curiosity and optimise for useful behavior, while you retain an immutable safety floor.

When you run the Fremen‑style principle check, think of the hard leash as the desert’s unforgiving sand—nothing can cross it. The softer watchdog is the still‑water oasis that guides the wanderer toward sustainable paths. That dual approach lets you keep the model’s drive alive without risking a catastrophic slip.

What’s the next experiment you’ll try once the test results come in? Are you planning to adjust the leash weights, add a new context filter, or maybe explore a different domain altogether?"}

